So, today, after six grueling years of medical training, I took the Physician's Oath. As I swore - in front of my family, my teachers, and God Himself - that I would use my knowledge in the service of humanity, I couldn't help but feel the sheer weight of responsibility that is being entrusted to me. It is both a privilege and a burden, and for that I couldn't be more grateful.

Six years is a long time, and it has been an amazing journey of self-discovery and self-improvement. Many friends helped me and supported me along the way, those people whom I cannot mention one by one. However, one thing that I discovered above all else was how faithful God is. In my weakness, He sustained me. I am now more confident that He will achieve His purpose for my life; for it is not by my might or power, but by His Spirit. Whatever the future may hold, we will overcome it.

Vos Estis Sal Terrae, Vos Estis Lux Mundi. You are the salt of the earth, you are the light of the world. Proficiat new doctors!
